Blog Your Solution: Red Wine Quality¶

Business Understanding¶

Problem Definition¶

This is a tidy data set, containing 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. The quality of this red wine has been rated by at least 3 experts with values ranging from 0 (very bad) to 10 (very excellent). In this project, I am going to understand, prepare and model this dataset, while answering some important research questions. Get the data set from here.

Assess Situation¶

Of course it's logical to conclude that high quality wines are most expensive, but we must be able to know how to determine the quality of red wine, based on it's chemical components. If you are a consumer, you may stand the risk of buying low quality wine at very high prices. On the other hand, it's possible that a company will be more exposed to DBI if they do not understand fully how the wine quality is affected by it's chemical constituents.

Goals for the Business¶

We are going to use this red wine data set to answer some questions usually asked by red wine coumers and it manufacturers

  1. Which is of high quality? Low alcoholic red wines or high alcoholic red wines
  3. How do we predict the quality of red wine from it chemical components?

Data Understanding¶

In the code cell below we load the red wine quality dataset into pandas DataFrame. The dataset contains 1599 observations(rows of the resulting dataframe) and 11 variables (columns of the resulting dataframe) involved in assessing quality of red wine.

Data preparation¶

Identification of data issues¶

This is a tidy data set, meaning it's doesn't have missing values, this can be confirmed below.

In [6]:
# Display the percentage of missing values in each feature
def missing_values(data):
    """
    Print out percentage of missing values in data set
    
    Parameter
    ---------
    data : DataFrame
        data set to explore
    
    Return
    ------
    Print out of features with more than )% of missing values
    """
    missing_data = []
    percentage_missing_data =(data.isnull().sum()/len(data))
    print("Percentage of Missing data")
    for x in range(len(percentage_missing_data)):
        if(percentage_missing_data[x] > 0):
            missing_data = percentage_missing_data.index[x]
            print("{} has {:.1f}% of data marked as NaNs".format(missing_data, (percentage_missing_data[x]*100)))

missing_values(df)

Question 1: How do the acidity and quantity of chlorides affect red wine quality?¶

In [11]:
#Group data by Quality to get some insights
test_data.groupby("Quality")['pH']
#get the average values of fixed acidity and chlorides
test_data.groupby('Quality')[["fixed.acidity","chlorides"]].mean()
Out[11]:
fixed.acidity chlorides
Quality
High_Quality 8.474035 0.082661
Low_Quality 8.142204 0.092989

We notice from the table above that the average acidity of red wines is higher for high quality wines and lower for low quality wines. On the otherhand, the average chlorides quantity is higher for low quality wines and lower for high quality wines. These mean that, companies are advised to increase the acidity of red wine and reduce the chlorides contents to increase quality.

Question 3: How do we predict the quality of red wine from it chemical components?¶

To answer this question, we need modeling, we will exploit two models.

Modelling¶

We are going to use two models(Logistic Regression Model, Support Vector Classifier) and then select the best.

Split the dataset into training and testing sets¶
In [24]:
# Here we would also split the data into a training and testing set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size =0.30, random_state=42)

Model 1: Logistic Regression¶

In [25]:
lgr = LogisticRegression()
lgr.fit(X_train, y_train)
lgr_predicted = lgr.predict(X_test)
print('Accuracy of logistic regression on test set: {:.3f}'.format(lgr.score(X_test, y_test)))

Validation¶

To improve the accuracy of our models, we must do this by tuning hyperpareameters through GridSearchCV and using Cross Validaton Score to select the best and optimized model our predictions.

Cross Validation¶

Cross validation is aimed at avoiding overfitting and giving a more precise prediction for each observation dataset. 10-fold Cross-Validation will be used to train our Logistic Regression and the support vector classifier models.

In [28]:
#setting the default kfold value 
kfold = model_selection.KFold(n_splits=10, random_state=7)
In [29]:
#crossvalidating the logistic regression model 10kfold
scoring = 'accuracy'
results = model_selection.cross_val_score(lgr, X_train, y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
print("Average accuracy for Logistic Regression: %.2f" % (results.mean()))

#cross validation average accuracy for Vector Support Classifier 10kfold
svc_eval = cross_val_score(estimator = svc, X = X_train, y = y_train, cv=kfold, scoring=scoring)
print('Average accuracy for support vector classifier: %.2f'%(svc_eval.mean()))

Average accuracy for Logistic Regression: 0.75
Average accuracy for support vector classifier: 0.70

Tuning Hyperparameter using GridSearchCV¶

here we will test various hyperparameters using the GridSearchCV for both models

In [30]:
# Create regularization hyperparameter space
C_space = np.logspace(0, 2, 20)
In [31]:
# Creating the penalty space
penalty = ['l1', 'l2']
hyperparameters = dict(C=C_space, penalty=penalty)

#grid searching with 10-fold cross validation
clf = GridSearchCV(lgr, hyperparameters, cv=10, verbose=0)
# Fitting the grid search
best_model = clf.fit(X, y)

# best hyperparameters
s_penalty=best_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['penalty']
s_c=best_model.best_estimator_.get_params()['C']
# Get the resulting accuracy
lgr_search = LogisticRegression(penalty=s_penalty,C=s_c)
lgr_search.fit(X_train, y_train)
predicted_lgr_search = lgr_search.predict(X_test)

print('Accuracy of logistic regression on test set: {:.2f}'.format(lgr_search.score(X_test, y_test)))

Accuracy of logistic regression on test set: 0.74

  • After GridSearchCV hyperparameters tuning applied for both models. Logistic Regression model performed(74%) better than the Support Vector classifier model(70%). Therefore, we selected the Logistic regression model.
Checking the precision, recall, F-score, support and the confusion matrix¶

The precision = true positive / (true positive + false ppositive).

Recall=True Predicted Positive/Total Actuall positive

The F1-Score is the balance between Precision and Recall.

The the number of occurrences of each class in y_test is the Support.

In [33]:
